<h2 id=3D"4">ocaml-letsencrypt, an OCaml way to get TLS certificates</h2>
<div class=3D"outline-text-2" id=3D"text-4">
<p>
Archive: <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-ocaml-letsencrypt-an-oc=
aml-way-to-get-tls-certificates/17975/1">https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-oc=
aml-letsencrypt-an-ocaml-way-to-get-tls-certificates/17975/1</a>
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgf5aa4a9" class=3D"outline-3">
<h3 id=3D"orgf5aa4a9">Calascibetta Romain announced</h3>
<div class=3D"outline-text-3" id=3D"text-orgf5aa4a9">
<p>
I am delighted to announce the release of <a href=3D"https://github.com/rob=
ur-coop/ocaml-letsencrypt">ocaml-letsencrypt</a> (version 2.1.0). This vers=
ion introduces a new API that allows it to operate independently of a sched=
uler and an HTTP client. It is also a rewrite using our brand-new <a href=
=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/jws">jws</a> library, which now utilises =
the <a href=3D"https://erratique.ch/logiciel/jsont">jsont</a> library (rath=
er than <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocaml-community/yojson">yojson</a>).
</p>

<p>
<code>ocaml-letsencrypt</code> implements <a href=3D"https://letsencrypt.or=
g/fr/docs/challenge-types/">challenges</a> needed to obtain a certificate v=
ia the three ways: DNS, HTTP and ACME-TLS. It therefore enables a website d=
eployment strategy (implemented with <a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-co=
op/vif">Vif</a>, for example) to be provided entirely in OCaml.
</p>

<p>
We use it within our cooperative for projects such as:
</p>
<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/dns-letsencrypt-secondary/"><c=
ode>dns-letsencrypt-secondary</code></a>, a unikernel that acts as a second=
ary DNS server capable of performing the DNS challenge for a specific domai=
n and generating the certificate and private key. It generally works in tan=
dem with our <a href=3D"https://github.com/robur-coop/dns-primary-git"><cod=
e>primary-git</code></a>, our primary DNS server.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://github.com/dinosaure/contruno"><code>contruno</code>=
</a>, a unikernel that acts as a TLS reverse proxy and is capable of perfor=
ming HTTP challenges. The latter is currently being completely rewritten us=
ing <a href=3D"https://discuss.ocaml.org/t/ann-mnet-a-new-tcp-ip-stack-for-=
unikernels-in-ocaml/17851"><code>mnet</code></a>.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Good luck with deploying your websites, and happy hacking! Here=E2=80=99s h=
oping that <code>jws</code> also finds its place as a library within the OC=
aml ecosystem.
</p>
</div>
</div>
