print_endline <span style=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">[%=
i18n</span> foo <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">~lang</s=
pan>:<span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">My_i18n.</span><spa=
n style=3D"color: #242521;">Fr</span><span style=3D"color: #a7601f; backgro=
und-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>;
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
The current language is held in a mutable reference you can swap (or replac=
e with an Eliom scoped reference if you need per-session/tab languages).
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org72492cb" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"org72492cb">Dune integration</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-org72492cb">
<p>
The tool plugs into Dune very naturally. Generate the OCaml module from you=
r TSV file with a rule:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-lisp"><code>(rule
 (target example_i18n.ml)
 (deps example_i18n.tsv)
 (action
  (run %{bin:ocsigen-i18n} --languages en,fr --input-file %{deps}
                           --output-file %{target})))
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
And wire the PPX in your library/executable:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-lisp"><code>(preprocess (pps ocsigen-i18n -- --defaul=
t-module Example_i18n))
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
That=E2=80=99s all you need for a plain OCaml project.
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgd92bc98" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"orgd92bc98">Tyxml support</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-orgd92bc98">
<p>
Pass <code>--tyxml</code> to the generator and the same <code>[%i18n key]</=
code> expression now produces a <b>list of Tyxml HTML elements</b> instead =
of a string:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-styl=
e: italic;">(* </span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">B=
uilds an HTML fragment, ready to drop into a Tyxml tree</span><span style=
=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)</span>
<span style=3D"color: #242521; font-weight: bold;">let</span> <span style=
=3D"color: #007a9f;">greeting</span> =3D <span style=3D"color: #a7601f; bac=
kground-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> bar <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; f=
ont-weight: bold;">~x</span>:[<span style=3D"color: #9f0d0f;">%</span>i18n =
a_human]<span style=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
Variables can themselves be lists of HTML nodes, so you can mix translated =
text with markup naturally:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #a7601f; backgroun=
d-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> bar <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-we=
ight: bold;">~x</span>:[ txt <span style=3D"color: #ca3400;">"Jean-Michel (=
"</span>
              ; txt (string_of_int id)
              ; txt <span style=3D"color: #ca3400;">")"</span> ]<span style=
=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
If you need a plain string in Tyxml mode (for an attribute, for instance), =
just prefix with <code>S.</code>:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #a7601f; backgroun=
d-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> <span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight=
: bold;">S.</span>bar <span style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">~x=
</span>:[<span style=3D"color: #9f0d0f;">%</span>i18n <span style=3D"color:=
 #557400; font-weight: bold;">S.</span>a_human]<span style=3D"color: #a7601=
f; background-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>   <span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; fo=
nt-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: ita=
lic;">string output</span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic=
;"> *)</span>
</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-org78184ed" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"org78184ed">Eliom support</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-org78184ed">
<p>
For client=E2=80=93server Eliom apps, pass <code>--eliom</code>. The genera=
tor emits an <code>.eliom</code> file (so the same translations are availab=
le on both sides), implies <code>--tyxml</code>, and adds <code>[@@deriving=
 json]</code> on the language type so you can serialise it across the wire:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-lisp"><code>(rule
 (target example_i18n.eliom)
 (deps example_i18n.tsv)
 (action
  (run %{bin:ocsigen-i18n} --eliom --languages en,fr --input-file %{deps}
                           --output-file %{target})))
</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div id=3D"outline-container-orgb5d5770" class=3D"outline-4">
<h4 id=3D"orgb5d5770">Multiple TSV files</h4>
<div class=3D"outline-text-4" id=3D"text-orgb5d5770">
<p>
You can split translations across several files. The PPX uses your module p=
ath to find the right one:
</p>

<div class=3D"org-src-container">
<pre class=3D"src src-ocaml"><code><span style=3D"color: #a7601f; backgroun=
d-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> foo<span style=3D"color: #a7601f; backgrou=
nd-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>                          <span style=3D"color:=
 #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; fon=
t-style: italic;">default module</span><span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-=
style: italic;"> *)</span>
<span style=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> <s=
pan style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">MyI18n.</span>foo<span sty=
le=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">]</span>                 =
  <span style=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">(* </span><span style=
=3D"color: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;">MyI18n.foo</span><span style=3D"co=
lor: #8f6f4a; font-style: italic;"> *)</span>
<span style=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">[%i18n</span> <s=
pan style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;">MyI18n.S.</span>bar <span =
style=3D"color: #444fcf; font-weight: bold;">~x</span>:[<span style=3D"colo=
r: #9f0d0f;">%</span>i18n <span style=3D"color: #557400; font-weight: bold;=
">S.</span>foo]<span style=3D"color: #a7601f; background-color: #ebebeb;">]=
</span>
</code></pre>
</div>

<p>
Optional <code>--prefix</code> / <code>--suffix</code> flags let you keep c=
all-sites concise (<code>[%i18n Feature.foo]</code> =E2=86=92 <code>Pr_Feat=
ure_i18n.foo ()</code>).
</p>

<p>
&mdash;
</p>

<ul class=3D"org-ul">
<li>Sources: <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocsigen/ocsigen-i18n">https://gi=
thub.com/ocsigen/ocsigen-i18n</a></li>
<li>Documentation: README on the repo</li>
<li>Bug reports: <a href=3D"https://github.com/ocsigen/ocsigen-i18n/issues"=
>https://github.com/ocsigen/ocsigen-i18n/issues</a></li>
</ul>

<p>
Happy translating!
</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
